What is a Pushdown Automaton (PDA)?

A PDA is like a finite automaton but with a stack.
It helps recognize context-free languages (CFLs) â€” the ones CFGs describe.

1. PDA Definition

A PDA is a 7-tuple:
(Q,Î£,Î“,Î´,q0,Z0,F)

Where:

Q: Set of states
Î£: Input alphabet
Î“: Stack alphabet

Î´: Transition function
â€‹

: Start state
â€‹

: Initial stack symbol

ğ¹
F: Set of accepting states

2. Transition Diagram (How it works)

Transitions are written as:

Î´(q,a,X)=(p,Î³)

This means:

In state q

Reading input a

Seeing X at top of stack
â†’ Move to state p and replace X with Î³ on the stack

âœ… Stack is Last In, First Out (LIFO)

3. Instantaneous Description (ID)

An ID shows the current state, remaining input, and stack content:

(q,w,Î±)

Where:

q is the current state

w is the unprocessed input

Î± is the current stack (top on the left)

4. Acceptance Types

PDA can accept strings in two ways:

âœ” By Final State:

Machine reaches an accepting state after input is done.

âœ” By Empty Stack:

Input is done, and stack is empty (even if state is not final).

Both are valid â€” and for every PDA accepting by one method, there's another PDA accepting the same language by the other.

5. CFG â†” PDA Conversions
âœ” CFG â†’ PDA

You can build a PDA from any CFG that:

Starts with the start variable on the stack

Replaces variables using CFG rules (like leftmost derivation)

Matches terminals by popping them when reading input

âœ” PDA â†’ CFG

You can also convert a PDA into a CFG, but itâ€™s more technical.

For now: most board questions ask CFG â†’ PDA or ask you to design a PDA from a language.

ğŸ“Œ Must Master: Design PDA for simple CFLs
ğŸ¯ Example Language:

L = { aâ¿bâ¿ | n â‰¥ 0 }
(equal number of aâ€™s followed by bâ€™s)

âœ… Idea:

Push each a onto the stack

For each b, pop an a

If the stack is empty after input â†’ accept



This PDA accepts all strings like:

Îµ, ab, aabb, aaabbb, etc.





